Here is some C# code that implements the quicksort algorithm for sorting an unsorted array of integers:

```
static void QuickSort(int[] array, int start, int end)
{
    if (start < end)
    {
        int index = Partition(array, start, end);
        QuickSort(array, start, index - 1);
        QuickSort(array, index + 1, end);
    }
}

static int Partition(int[] array, int start, int end)
{
    int index = Partition(array, start, end, array[start]);
    Swap(array, start, index);
    return index;
}

static void Swap(int[] array, int first, int second)
{
    int temp = array[first];
    array[first] = array[second];
    array[second] = temp;
}
```

Here `QuickSort` takes an array of integers, `array`, and two indices `start` and `end`, which specify the range of the array to be sorted. Within the function, `Partition` takes the same parameters as `QuickSort` and returns the index of the pivot element. Then, `QuickSort` is called recursively on the subarrays `[start, index - 1]` and `[index + 1, end]`. Finally, `Swap` swaps the elements at indices `first` and `second`, which are the indices of the pivot and the element to the right of the pivot in the original array.

