A stack is a data structure that stores and manipulates data in the form of a finite, ordered sequence of elements, known as the stack data structure. The elements in a stack are stored in a last-in-first-out (LIFO) manner, meaning that the last element added will be the first one to be removed. It is often used to represent a resource that can only be consumed, and is used to implement algorithms such as sorting or searching.

A stack works by maintaining a stack frame for each element in the stack. Each frame contains information about the element, such as its position in the stack and the stack size. When an element is pushed onto the stack, a new frame is created for it and the stack frame for the element at the top of the stack is updated to reflect the new size of the stack. When an element is popped from the stack, the top stack frame is updated to reflect the new size of the stack and the frame for the popped element is deleted. This way, the stack is always in a valid state.

A queue is another data structure that stores and manipulates data in the form of a finite, ordered sequence of elements. Unlike a stack, a queue is a first-in-first-out (FIFO) data structure, meaning that the first element added will be the first one to be removed. It is often used to implement algorithms such as sorting or searching, and to represent a resource that can be consumed but not depleted.

A queue works by maintaining a queue frame for each element in the queue. Each frame contains information about the element, such as its position in the queue and the queue size. When an element is enqueued, a new frame is created for it and the queue frame for the element at the front of the queue is updated to reflect the new size of the queue. When an element is dequeued, the top queue frame is updated to reflect the new size of the queue and the frame for the dequeued element is deleted. This way, the queue is always in a valid state.

In pseudocode, here's an example of a basic implementation of a queue data structure in Java:

```
class Queue {
    // define instance variables
    private int front, back;
    private Object[] data;

    // constructor
    public Queue() {
        front = back = 0;
        data = new Object[10];
    }

    // enqueue an element
    public void enqueue(Object o) {
        if (front >= back) {
            throw new IllegalStateException("The queue is full!");
        }
        data[front] = o;
        back++;
        front++;
    }

    // dequeue an element
    public Object dequeue() {
        if (front == back) {
            throw new IllegalStateException("The queue is empty!");
        }
        Object o = data[front];
        back--;
        front--;
        return o;
    }
}
```

